    "plainText": "DELIVERIES REQUIREMENTS OVERVIEW\n\nMaterial receiving, routing, unloading, and delivery-area control for active construction sites\n\nDeliveries control how materials, tools, equipment, and vendor traffic enter the jobsite and interact with workers already in the work area. This document follows the approved sectioned format and limits the content to requirements that pertain to delivery planning, unloading activity, and the control of delivery-related exposure on site.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Vehicle movement  Delivery activity can create struck-by exposure, blind-spot issues, backing conflicts, and mixed worker and vehicle traffic when routes and unloading points are not established before arrival (R1).\n\n1.2 Unloading exposure  Loads can shift, fall, roll, or swing during unloading if the surface is unstable, the material is poorly secured, or the receiving crew is not clear on the handling method (R6).\n\n1.3 Congestion and access  Poorly timed or poorly placed deliveries can block emergency access, crowd staging areas, and force workers to move around active equipment in tight conditions (R9).\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Pre-construction planning  Before delivery work begins, the site should identify routes, unloading points, backup areas, spotter locations, overhead conflicts, and where material will be staged after arrival (R1).\n\n2.2 Pre-task review  Daily review should confirm current site conditions, ground support, weather, active work near the route, and whether any special lift, escort, or traffic-control measure is needed before the truck enters the site (R2).\n\n2.3 Site logistics  The delivery plan should keep pedestrians separated from moving equipment and should be updated when the workface, storage pattern, or jobsite density changes (R7).\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Unloading surfaces  Delivery and unload areas should be firm, level enough for the intended equipment, and capable of supporting the load, axle weight, and material handling activity expected during receipt (R1).\n\n3.2 Material support  Pallets, dunnage, racks, blocking, and temporary supports used during delivery should keep materials from settling, tipping, or shifting after they are placed (R5).\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Temporary delivery controls  For deliveries, this section applies to dock plates, ramps, temporary barriers, exclusion-zone markings, wheel chocks, and similar controls used to support safe material transfer rather than permanent decking work.\n\n4.2 Secure transfer  Temporary devices used for unloading should be placed and maintained so they do not slide, separate, or fail when exposed to load movement, vibration, repeated use, or equipment contact (R6).\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 General training  Workers involved in receiving deliveries should be instructed on struck-by hazards, exclusion zones, route awareness, housekeeping around unload points, and the need to stay clear of suspended or shifting loads (R2).\n\n5.2 Task-specific training  Personnel receiving material should understand the delivery plan, communication method with the driver or operator, unloading sequence, and the limits of the area being controlled.\n\n5.2.1 Equipment-related training  Where deliveries involve forklifts, telehandlers, cranes, pallet jacks, or other powered handling equipment, only personnel with the appropriate training, qualification, or experience should perform the task (R10).\n\n5.2.2 Update training  Additional instruction should be provided whenever routes, unloading points, material type, or equipment needs change enough to alter delivery risk (R2).\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 General applicability  Deliveries do not normally create a stand-alone certification requirement simply because materials are being received.\n\n6.2 When certifications apply  Documented qualifications may still be needed when the work involves powered industrial trucks, telehandlers, cranes, signal persons, rigging duties, or owner-required receiving controls (R6).\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Basic control equipment  Typical delivery-control equipment includes cones, barriers, wheel chocks, radios, taglines, pallet jacks, forklifts, telehandlers, and signs used to isolate the unloading area.\n\n7.2 Support equipment  Additional items may include dunnage, racks, load securement tools, high-visibility garments, gloves, and lighting where delivery activity continues in low-light conditions (R8).\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 Delivery permits  Deliveries themselves do not usually require a unique permit, but site-specific authorization may still be required for controlled entry or after-hours receiving.\n\n8.2 Related permit triggers  Permit or approval requirements may apply where deliveries involve crane lifts, roadway occupancy, traffic control, oversized loads, or owner-controlled access restrictions.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected by Deliveries Requirements\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  These requirements most directly affect laborers, operators, drivers, riggers, signal persons, supervision, and material handlers who participate in receipt and unload operations.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Any trade working adjacent to unload zones, haul routes, or staging areas is also affected because delivery activity changes access, visibility, and movement patterns on the site (R7).\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Ongoing control  Delivery control should be treated as an active process rather than a gate-only function. Routes, unload areas, and timing should be adjusted when congestion, weather, or changing work fronts reduce the effectiveness of the original plan (R1).\n\n10.2 Access and cleanup  Delivery areas should be kept orderly after receipt so broken pallets, strapping, packaging, or displaced material do not create a second hazard after the truck leaves (R3).\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document. Source language is shortened for space and tied to OSHA construction standards and the OSHA construction digest materials used to support this task document.\n\nR1. Employers shall initiate and maintain programs necessary to comply with Part 1926, including frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR2. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. 29 CFR 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR3. Debris shall be kept cleared from work areas, passageways, and stairs, and containers shall be provided for collection and separation of waste and refuse. 29 CFR 1926.25(a)-(c).\n\nR4. Construction areas, aisles, stairs, ramps, runways, corridors, offices, shops, and storage areas where work is in progress shall be lighted with natural or artificial illumination. 29 CFR 1926.26.\n\nR5. Materials stored in tiers shall be stacked, racked, blocked, interlocked, or otherwise secured to prevent sliding, falling, or collapse. 29 CFR 1926.250(b)(1).\n\nR6. Rigging equipment for material handling shall be inspected and used in a manner that supports safe lifting and load control. 29 CFR 1926.251.\n\nR7. Motor vehicles and mechanized equipment used in off-highway jobsite areas must be operated under jobsite safety controls and maintained with required safety features. 29 CFR 1926.601; OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, Motor Vehicles and Mechanized Equipment.\n\nR8. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment where employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. 29 CFR 1926.28(a).\n\nR9. Exits shall be arranged and maintained to provide free and unobstructed egress, and access to exits shall be marked where not immediately visible. 29 CFR 1926.34(a)-(c).\n\nR10. The employer shall permit only those employees qualified by training or experience to operate equipment and machinery. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(4).",
