    "plainText": "HAZARD ASSESSMENT REQUIREMENTS OVERVIEW\n\nField hazard review controls for recognizing exposures and aligning protections before work proceeds\n\nHazard assessment is the process of identifying the conditions, activities, and interfaces that can expose workers, equipment, materials, or the public to injury, loss, or disruption. It should be specific to the actual work area and should drive the controls used in the field rather than exist as a generic checklist only.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Unrecognized exposure  The main hazard in a weak assessment is that crews move into the work without identifying the actual exposure from access, equipment, stored materials, overhead work, energy sources, weather, or changing site conditions (R1).\n\n1.2 Incomplete control selection  If hazards are listed in a generic way, the crew may use controls that look compliant on paper but do not match the real work activity, location, or sequence.\n\n1.3 Communication gaps  A hazard that is known by one supervisor but not clearly communicated to the rest of the crew can still result in injury, near miss, or property damage during execution (R2).\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Area review  The assessment should start with a field walk that reviews the work area, access points, nearby trades, stored materials, utilities, traffic paths, and any condition that could change during the task (R1).\n\n2.2 Hazard ranking  The crew should identify which hazards require immediate physical controls, which depend on permits or shutdowns, and which will need ongoing monitoring during the work.\n\n2.3 Reassessment  Hazard assessment should be repeated when weather changes, new trades enter the area, equipment is added, or the work moves into a different phase or location (R7).\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Surface condition  The assessment should verify that the ground, slab, deck, scaffold, access route, or temporary work surface is stable enough for the planned activity and the loads that will be introduced.\n\n3.2 Adjacent-condition review  Nearby excavation, unsupported materials, unstable edges, stacked items, or partially completed work should be reviewed because they can create secondary hazards even when they are outside the immediate task area.\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Opening and edge review  The assessment should confirm whether temporary covers, ramps, barriers, railings, crossings, or platform sections are needed to keep the work area usable and controlled.\n\n4.2 Condition verification  Where temporary access or protective systems are already in place, they should be checked to confirm they remain secure, complete, and appropriate for the work now being performed.\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 General training  Employees should be instructed in how to recognize the hazards connected to their work environment and the controls expected before the task proceeds (R2).\n\n5.2 Task-specific training  Additional instruction may be needed for exposed energy, high-risk interfaces, environmental conditions, or owner-specific controls that are not obvious to new or reassigned workers.\n\n5.2.1 Competent-person involvement  Where the activity depends on a competent person review, that person should understand the type of exposure being assessed and have authority to require corrective action (R7).\n\n5.2.2 Update training  If the hazard picture changes enough to affect the method of work, the crew should receive an updated review before continuing.\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 General applicability  Hazard assessment itself does not usually create a standalone certification requirement.\n\n6.2 When certifications apply  Documented qualifications may still be required when the assessment covers regulated roles such as excavation competent person, operator qualification, specialized testing, or permit-authorizing responsibilities.\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Assessment tools  Typical hazard-assessment tools include task plans, drawings, permits, radios, flashlights, gas-testing devices where applicable, measuring tools, barricade materials, and inspection tags.\n\n7.2 Protective equipment  The assessment should also identify the PPE and temporary controls needed for the task, including head, eye, hand, visibility, fall, or respiratory protection where exposure requires it (R5).\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 Permit linkage  Hazard assessment should confirm whether the identified exposure triggers permits such as excavation, confined space, hot work, crane activity, or temporary electrical work.\n\n8.2 Hold-point authority  When a permit or owner authorization is part of the control strategy, the hazard assessment should clearly show that work cannot proceed until that approval is active.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected by Hazard Assessment Requirements\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  These requirements most directly affect supervisors, foremen, competent persons, operators, and the crews performing the work because they rely on the assessment to understand real exposure.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Nearby trades, delivery personnel, and maintenance staff may also be affected if the assessed hazards involve shared access, overlapping work zones, or temporary route changes.\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Field-specific focus  The best hazard assessments describe the actual exposure in the actual work area instead of relying on generic wording that could apply anywhere.\n\n10.2 Record value  Brief documentation of changing hazards, added controls, and corrective actions can support later review and help strengthen future planning for similar work.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document. Source language is shortened for space and tied to the OSHA construction standards and OSHA construction digest materials used for this prototype.\n\nR1. Employers shall initiate and maintain programs necessary to comply with Part 1926, including frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR2. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. 29 CFR 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR5. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment where employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. 29 CFR 1926.28(a).\n\nR7. Employees must be trained in a language and vocabulary they can understand, and employers must provide competent person oversight and frequent inspections. OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, General section.",
