    "plainText": "HOUSEKEEPING REQUIREMENTS OVERVIEW\n\nDaily control of debris, scrap, access routes, and work-area cleanliness during construction operations\n\nHousekeeping supports safe movement, efficient work, and consistent control of debris, scrap, waste, and trip hazards across the project. This document follows the approved sectioned format and limits the content to requirements that pertain to keeping work areas, passageways, stairs, and adjacent spaces usable and controlled during active construction.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Debris accumulation  Poor housekeeping can create slip, trip, puncture, and fire exposure when scrap, packaging, cords, protruding nails, or loose material are allowed to build up in active work areas (R3).\n\n1.2 Blocked access  Cluttered stairs, corridors, ramps, ladders, or passageways can delay production, reduce visibility, and interfere with routine movement as well as emergency egress (R8).\n\n1.3 Secondary exposure  Combustible waste, poor container use, and mixed storage of scrap and materials can create avoidable hazards that affect multiple trades beyond the original work area (R4).\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Pre-construction planning  Housekeeping expectations should be established before work begins so the site has assigned cleanup points, debris routes, waste containers, and a clear understanding of who is responsible for cleanup at each phase (R1).\n\n2.2 Pre-task review  Daily planning should confirm what waste streams will be generated, what areas must remain open, where cleanup will occur during the shift, and whether any trade is creating an unusual debris condition (R2).\n\n2.3 Site logistics  Cleanup sequencing should support work progress by keeping exits, access ways, and staging edges open rather than waiting until the end of the shift to address known buildup (R8).\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Walking surfaces  Housekeeping depends on stable walking and working surfaces that are not overloaded with debris, scrap piles, or unsecured stored material that can shift underfoot.\n\n3.2 Temporary supports  Bins, dumpsters, carts, shelving, and temporary scrap-control devices should remain placed on suitable surfaces so they do not settle, lean, or spill into access paths (R10).\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Temporary controls  For housekeeping, this section applies to temporary trash stations, toe-board protection, deck-edge cleanup control, and temporary walk surfaces used to keep work areas clean rather than permanent decking work.\n\n4.2 Secure placement  Temporary cleanup devices should be positioned so they do not block movement or become loose from wind, contact, overfilling, or repeated relocation during the shift (R5).\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 General training  Workers should be instructed on the site housekeeping standard, debris removal expectations, access protection, container use, and the need to keep work areas clear throughout the shift rather than only at closeout (R2).\n\n5.2 Task-specific training  Personnel generating high volumes of scrap or packaging should understand how to separate materials, control protruding fasteners or sharp edges, and maintain clear travel paths around their work.\n\n5.2.1 Waste-stream training  Where cleanup includes flammable waste, sharp scrap, silica-containing dust, or other regulated material, the affected workers should be instructed on the handling precautions that may apply (R4).\n\n5.2.2 Update training  Additional instruction should be provided when site conditions change enough to affect cleanup routes, dumpster locations, or access expectations (R2).\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 General applicability  Housekeeping does not normally require a stand-alone certification simply because cleanup activity is being performed.\n\n6.2 When certifications apply  Documented qualifications may still be needed where housekeeping work involves powered equipment, regulated waste handling, or project-specific environmental controls.\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Basic control equipment  Typical housekeeping equipment includes trash containers, scrap bins, brooms, shovels, carts, magnetic sweepers, utility knives, and signage used to support cleanup and separation.\n\n7.2 Support equipment  Additional items may include covered cans for flammable or harmful waste, gloves, eye protection, dust-control tools, and lighting for enclosed or low-light cleanup areas (R6).\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 Housekeeping permits  Routine housekeeping does not usually create a unique permit requirement.\n\n8.2 Related permit triggers  Additional controls may apply when cleanup is performed inside permit spaces, during hot work, or while handling regulated or owner-controlled waste streams.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected by Housekeeping Requirements\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  These requirements most directly affect laborers, carpenters, concrete crews, drywall crews, electricians, mechanical trades, and supervision because each group both generates and is affected by debris in the work area.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Housekeeping is a shared site-control issue because one trade’s debris can block another trade’s access, work platform, or emergency route (R8).\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Ongoing control  Housekeeping should be continuous and visible. Conditions should be corrected when they are observed instead of carried forward from shift to shift (R1).\n\n10.2 Fire and egress  Combustible scrap control and clear exit access are basic parts of housekeeping quality because site cleanliness is directly tied to fire prevention and emergency response readiness (R4).\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document. Source language is shortened for space and tied to OSHA construction standards and the OSHA construction digest materials used to support this task document.\n\nR1. Employers shall initiate and maintain programs necessary to comply with Part 1926, including frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR2. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. 29 CFR 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR3. Form and scrap lumber with protruding nails and all other debris shall be kept clear from work areas, passageways, and stairs. 29 CFR 1926.25(a); OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, Housekeeping.\n\nR4. Combustible scrap and debris shall be removed at regular intervals and the employer shall develop and maintain an effective fire protection and prevention program. 29 CFR 1926.25(b); 29 CFR 1926.24.\n\nR5. Containers shall be provided for the collection and separation of waste, trash, oily and used rags, and other refuse; covered containers are required for flammable or harmful wastes. 29 CFR 1926.25(c).\n\nR6. Construction areas, aisles, stairs, ramps, runways, corridors, offices, shops, and storage areas where work is in progress shall be lighted with natural or artificial illumination. 29 CFR 1926.26.\n\nR7. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment where employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. 29 CFR 1926.28(a).\n\nR8. Exits shall be arranged and maintained to provide free and unobstructed egress, and access to exits shall be marked where not immediately visible. 29 CFR 1926.34(a)-(c).\n\nR9. Employees must be trained in a language and vocabulary they can understand, and employers must provide competent person oversight and frequent inspections. OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, General section.\n\nR10. Materials stored in tiers shall be stacked, racked, blocked, interlocked, or otherwise secured to prevent sliding, falling, or collapse. 29 CFR 1926.250(b)(1).",
