    "plainText": "PRE-TASK PLAN REQUIREMENTS OVERVIEW\n\nPre-activity planning controls for scope review, work sequencing, and day-of-task readiness\n\nPre-task planning establishes how the work will be performed before crews, equipment, and materials are committed to the operation. The goal is to align the scope, hazards, manpower, access, tools, permits, and sequence so the work starts in a controlled condition and stays coordinated through the shift.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Scope confusion  If the crew starts work without a clear review of the task, workers can act on different assumptions about limits of work, access points, equipment needs, or handoff responsibilities (R1).\n\n1.2 Sequence breakdown  A weak pre-task plan can place trades on top of one another, create avoidable rework, and increase exposure to struck-by, caught-between, and access hazards during startup (R10).\n\n1.3 Missed controls  Important controls such as lockout points, barricades, shutdown windows, delivery timing, or emergency routes can be overlooked when the work is not reviewed before the shift begins (R6).\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Scope review  The work should be reviewed before the shift to confirm what is being done, where it will occur, what resources are needed, and what conditions must be in place before crews begin (R1).\n\n2.2 Crew coordination  The pre-task discussion should identify responsible supervision, trade interfaces, material needs, equipment assignments, and the order in which the work will move through the area.\n\n2.3 Change management  If site conditions, manpower, or work sequence change during the day, the plan should be updated before the crew continues under new conditions (R2).\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Work-surface review  The plan should address whether the crew will work from stable grade, ladders, temporary stairs, platforms, or other surfaces that must be suitable for the intended load and activity.\n\n3.2 Temporary condition check  Any temporary support, access route, or adjacent condition that could affect safe work should be reviewed before the task starts, especially where weather, vibration, or material movement may change the condition of the area.\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Temporary access planning  Where the task relies on temporary ramps, covers, crossings, guardrails, or walkway sections, the pre-task plan should identify who installs, checks, and maintains those items before use.\n\n4.2 Interface control  The plan should also confirm that temporary barriers, deck openings, and access points will not be removed, shifted, or bypassed without communication to affected crews.\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 General training  Workers participating in the task should be instructed on the scope, known hazards, restricted areas, emergency routes, and expected controls before beginning work (R2).\n\n5.2 Task-specific training  Additional instruction may be needed for shutdown coordination, permit conditions, spotter duties, access controls, or specialized methods that are not part of routine work.\n\n5.2.1 Equipment-related training  If the task includes powered equipment, only personnel with the proper training or experience should operate the assigned equipment or direct its movement (R9).\n\n5.2.2 Update training  When the work plan changes enough to affect exposure, crew assignments, or sequence, the pre-task plan should be revised and re-communicated before the task resumes (R7).\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 General applicability  A pre-task plan does not usually require a standalone certification simply because the activity is called pre-task planning.\n\n6.2 When certifications apply  Documented qualifications may still be needed when the planned work involves operators, rigging personnel, permit authorizers, competent persons, or other roles controlled by project rules or regulation.\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Planning tools  Typical pre-task planning tools include current drawings, work permits, hazard review forms, radios, layout sketches, schedules, and communication boards or huddle materials.\n\n7.2 Support equipment  Depending on the task, the plan may also need PPE, inspection tags, access-control materials, light towers, temporary barriers, or hand tools ready before the crew mobilizes (R5).\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 Permit check  The pre-task plan should confirm whether the activity depends on permits such as hot work, excavation, confined space, energy isolation, traffic control, crane activity, or temporary power.\n\n8.2 Approval timing  Work should not start just because the crew is present if the controlling permit, shutdown authorization, or owner coordination has not been completed.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected by Pre-Task Plan Requirements\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  These requirements most directly affect supervision, labor leads, operators, foremen, and the first crews entering the work area because they establish how the task begins and who controls it.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Every trade tied to the sequence, access, material flow, or shutdown window is affected because poor planning in one task can disrupt multiple operations across the site.\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Daily use  A pre-task plan works best when it is treated as a living field control rather than a one-time form completed only for recordkeeping (R1).\n\n10.2 Documentation  Brief notes on changed conditions, revised sequence, added hazards, or permit delays can help preserve accountability and improve the quality of later planning for similar work.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document. Source language is shortened for space and tied to the OSHA construction standards and OSHA construction digest materials used for this prototype.\n\nR1. Employers shall initiate and maintain programs necessary to comply with Part 1926, including frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR2. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. 29 CFR 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR5. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment where employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. 29 CFR 1926.28(a).\n\nR6. Exits shall be arranged and maintained to provide free and unobstructed egress, and access to exits shall be marked where not immediately visible. 29 CFR 1926.34(a)-(c).\n\nR7. Employees must be trained in a language and vocabulary they can understand, and employers must provide competent person oversight and frequent inspections. OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, General section.\n\nR9. The employer shall permit only those employees qualified by training or experience to operate equipment and machinery. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(4).\n\nR10. Motor vehicles and mechanized equipment used in off-highway jobsite areas must be operated under jobsite safety controls and maintained with required safety features. 29 CFR 1926.601; OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, Motor Vehicles and Mechanized Equipment.",
