    "plainText": "QUALITY WALKDOWNS REQUIREMENTS OVERVIEW\n\nField review, condition verification, and corrective-action controls for ongoing work quality\n\nQuality walkdowns establish a routine field review process for checking conditions, workmanship, protection measures, and readiness for the next phase of work. The goal is to identify issues early, confirm that completed work remains acceptable, and make corrections before defects, rework, or safety concerns spread into later operations.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Missed defects  If work areas are not walked routinely, damaged materials, incomplete installations, missing protections, or poor sequencing can remain unnoticed until the issue becomes larger and harder to correct (R1).\n\n1.2 Condition drift  Temporary protections, access routes, barricades, weather exposure, and housekeeping can deteriorate after installation, so a one-time check is often not enough to keep the area acceptable (R3).\n\n1.3 Turnover of bad work  When the next trade receives an area that has not been reviewed, quality problems can be buried behind later work and create conflict, delays, and accountability gaps.\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Walkdown scope  Before the review begins, the walkdown should define which area, phase, or installation is being checked, what acceptance points apply, and who is responsible for documenting corrections.\n\n2.2 Interface review  The walkdown should include items that affect the next trade, such as access readiness, protection of finished work, incomplete punch items, and whether the area is actually ready to be released.\n\n2.3 Follow-up timing  Deficiencies should be assigned and rechecked within a defined timeframe so the walkdown becomes a working control instead of a list that sits unresolved (R2).\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Surface and support review  The review should look at slabs, edges, temporary stairs, platforms, support points, and material storage surfaces where settlement, damage, or instability could affect the quality and usability of the area.\n\n3.2 Exposure conditions  Walkdowns should consider whether weather, impact, vibration, loading, or adjacent work has changed the condition of installed items since the last check.\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Protection verification  Where the work depends on covers, ramps, crossings, deck openings, or temporary barriers, the walkdown should confirm those items remain secured, intact, and correctly placed.\n\n4.2 Interface completeness  Transitions between systems should be checked so one completed area is not relying on missing attachments, loose edge protection, or temporary conditions left unresolved from prior work.\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 General training  Personnel performing quality walkdowns should understand the area being reviewed, the acceptance expectations, known hazards, PPE requirements, and how to escalate deficiencies that affect safety or quality (R2).\n\n5.2 Task-specific training  Additional instruction may be required when walkdowns involve specialized systems, protection measures, owner requirements, or release criteria for a particular phase of work.\n\n5.2.1 Qualified review roles  When the walkdown includes regulated equipment, temporary systems, or technical installations, the review should involve personnel with the training or experience needed to recognize unacceptable conditions (R9).\n\n5.2.2 Documentation training  Supervisors and assigned reviewers should know how to document deficiencies clearly so corrections can be tracked, communicated, and closed without confusion (R7).\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 General applicability  Quality walkdowns do not normally require a standalone certification simply because the task is a walkdown.\n\n6.2 When certifications apply  Documented qualifications may still apply when the walkdown includes technical systems, equipment inspections, or regulated activities that must be reviewed by qualified personnel.\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Review tools  Typical walkdown tools include current drawings, deficiency lists, radios, flashlights, marking tools, cameras, and simple measuring or checking devices appropriate to the work area.\n\n7.2 Protective equipment  Review personnel should also have the PPE and access equipment needed to enter the area safely and inspect conditions without bypassing controls (R5).\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 Area-access permits  If the walkdown enters a permit-controlled area such as hot work, confined space, energized work, or restricted shutdown space, the review should follow the controlling permit requirements before entry.\n\n8.2 Release limitations  An area should not be accepted or released during the walkdown if the required permit conditions, protections, or owner restrictions are still unresolved.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected by Quality Walkdowns Requirements\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  These requirements most directly affect supervision, quality reviewers, foremen, and the next trade receiving the work area because the walkdown helps determine whether the area is actually ready.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Every trade is affected because unresolved defects, missing protections, or poor closeout of one phase usually become someone else’s problem in the next phase.\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Routine value  Quality walkdowns are most effective when they occur regularly and before major handoffs, not only after a problem becomes visible or expensive (R1).\n\n10.2 Clean area standard  A walkdown should also consider housekeeping and egress because an area that is physically unsafe or cluttered is not truly ready for the next operation (R3).\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR1. Employers shall initiate and maintain programs necessary to comply with Part 1926, including frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR2. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. 29 CFR 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR3. Debris, scrap material, and other waste shall be cleared from work areas, passageways, and stairs, and waste shall be removed at frequent and regular intervals. 29 CFR 1926.25(a)-(c).\n\nR5. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment where employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. 29 CFR 1926.28(a).\n\nR6. Exits shall be arranged and maintained to provide free and unobstructed egress, and access to exits shall be marked where not immediately visible. 29 CFR 1926.34(a)-(c).\n\nR7. Employees must be trained in a language and vocabulary they can understand, and employers must provide competent person oversight and frequent inspections. OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, General section.\n\nR9. The employer shall permit only those employees qualified by training or experience to operate equipment and machinery. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(4).\n\nR10. Motor vehicles and mechanized equipment used in off-highway jobsite areas must be operated under jobsite safety controls and maintained with required safety features. 29 CFR 1926.601; OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, Motor Vehicles and Mechanized Equipment.",
