    "plainText": "SIGNAGE REQUIREMENTS OVERVIEW\n\nVisual communication controls for identifying hazards, directing movement, and reinforcing site requirements\n\nSignage helps communicate hazards, mandatory controls, routes of travel, restricted areas, and emergency information in a form that can be recognized quickly. This document follows the same section structure used in the reference overview and keeps the content limited to requirements that pertain to signs used for site control, warning, instruction, and emergency communication.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Missing communication  Where required signs are missing or poorly placed, workers and visitors may enter restricted areas, miss route information, or fail to understand active hazards before exposure occurs (R11).\n\n1.2 Poor visibility  Signs that are obstructed, damaged, unlit, or lost in visual clutter can fail when they are most needed, especially in startup areas, low-light conditions, or busy access points (R4).\n\n1.3 Inconsistent instruction  Conflicting, outdated, or unclear signage can weaken site control and cause confusion about access restrictions, PPE expectations, and emergency routing (R5)(R6).\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Sign planning  Before work begins, the site should identify which signs are needed for entry points, restricted areas, traffic movement, emergency exits, material zones, and hazard-specific conditions.\n\n2.2 Placement review  Sign location should be planned so information is seen before the exposure is reached and not only after a worker has already entered the affected area.\n\n2.3 Ongoing update  The sign package should be reviewed as work sequence, manpower, routes, and controlled areas change so instructions remain accurate and useful.\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Mounting stability  Signs should be mounted on supports, fences, barriers, or rigid backings that keep them upright, legible, and resistant to normal weather and jobsite contact.\n\n3.2 Surface suitability  Temporary sign mounting should not rely on unstable, loose, or easily displaced supports that allow the sign to fall, twist, or face away from approaching traffic.\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Attachment and visibility  Signs should be secured in a way that keeps them visible and readable without interfering with walk surfaces, gate operation, or the protective function of the surface they are attached to.\n\n4.2 Temporary traffic surfaces  Where signs are placed near ramps, stairs, runways, or deck edges, the support should not create a trip hazard or reduce the clear width needed for safe access.\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 General training  Workers should be instructed on the meaning of the sign types used on the project, including warnings, restrictions, PPE requirements, route directions, and emergency information (R2)(R11).\n\n5.2 Task-specific training  Supervision and workers responsible for installing or updating signs should understand which messages are needed for each controlled area and when a sign must be changed or removed.\n\n5.2.1 Visitor and delivery communication  Where visitors, vendors, or delivery drivers are expected on site, personnel should know how signage supports screening, routing, and restricted access.\n\n5.2.2 Language and comprehension  Sign communication should support the workforce in a language and format that can reasonably be understood by those exposed to the condition (R7).\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 General applicability  Signage does not normally require a standalone certification.\n\n6.2 When certifications apply  Documented qualifications may still apply when sign installation is connected to electrical supports, traffic-control plans, or specialized public-way requirements.\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Basic signage equipment  Typical equipment includes warning signs, directional signs, restricted-access signs, emergency-route signs, reflective panels, stanchions, and mounting hardware.\n\n7.2 Support equipment  Additional items may include lights, barriers, ties, rigid backing, PPE, and temporary supports used to keep signs visible and protected in active work areas (R4)(R5).\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 General applicability  Signage itself does not usually create a unique permit requirement.\n\n8.2 Related permit triggers  Separate approvals may still apply where signs affect public streets, sidewalks, owner-controlled facilities, or traffic-control operations.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected by Signage Requirements\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  These requirements most directly affect all persons entering or moving through the project, including workers, visitors, supervisors, and delivery personnel.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Trades controlling restricted areas, emergency routes, staging, and site access rely on clear signage to keep surrounding personnel informed.\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Signs support, but do not replace, control  Signage should support physical controls and supervision, not replace them. A sign is most effective when it is paired with a barrier, a controlled route, or a monitored access point.\n\n10.2 Maintenance matters  Damaged, missing, or outdated signs should be corrected quickly because poor sign maintenance weakens the overall credibility of the site-control program (R11).\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document. Source language is shortened for space and tied to the OSHA construction standards and OSHA construction digest materials used for this task package.\n\nR1. Employers shall initiate and maintain programs necessary to comply with Part 1926, including frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR2. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. 29 CFR 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR3. Debris shall be kept cleared from work areas, passageways, and stairs, and containers shall be provided for collection and separation of waste and refuse. 29 CFR 1926.25(a)-(c).\n\nR4. Construction areas, aisles, stairs, ramps, runways, corridors, offices, shops, and storage areas where work is in progress shall be lighted with natural or artificial illumination. 29 CFR 1926.26.\n\nR5. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment where employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. 29 CFR 1926.28(a).\n\nR6. Exits shall be arranged and maintained to provide free and unobstructed egress, and access to exits shall be marked where not immediately visible. 29 CFR 1926.34(a)-(c).\n\nR7. Employees must be trained in a language and vocabulary they can understand, and employers must provide competent person oversight and frequent inspections. OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, General section.\n\nR8. Materials stored in tiers shall be stacked, racked, blocked, interlocked, or otherwise secured to prevent sliding, falling, or collapse. 29 CFR 1926.250(b)(1).\n\nR9. The employer shall permit only those employees qualified by training or experience to operate equipment and machinery. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(4).\n\nR10. Motor vehicles and mechanized equipment used in off-highway jobsite areas must be operated under jobsite safety controls and maintained with required safety features. 29 CFR 1926.601; OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, Motor Vehicles and Mechanized Equipment.\n\nR11. Accident prevention signs and tags should be used where needed to warn of hazards, caution against unsafe practices, or provide safety instruction. OSHA construction signs, signals, and barricade requirements under 29 CFR Part 1926.",
