    "moduleKey": "site_logistics_planning",
    "title": "Site Logistics Planning",
    "trade": "General Conditions / Site Management",
    "subTrade": "Safety / quality / logistics",
    "taskNames": [
      "Site logistics planning",
      "Site setup"
    ],
    "plainText": "SITE LOGISTICS PLANNING REQUIREMENTS OVERVIEW\n\nMovement, staging, access, and sequencing controls for organized site operations\n\nSite logistics planning establishes how workers, deliveries, materials, equipment, waste, and visitors will move through the project without creating conflict. The goal is to keep access, staging, support areas, and traffic paths organized so daily operations remain predictable, efficient, and safe as manpower and site density change.\n\n1. Risks & Hazards\n\n1.1 Route conflict  Without a clear logistics plan, deliveries, pedestrians, equipment, and trade crews can use the same paths at the same time, increasing the chance of congestion, backing incidents, and blocked access (R10).\n\n1.2 Poor staging control  If laydown, waste, and temporary storage areas are not defined, materials can spill into work zones, exits, or travel paths and create avoidable handling and housekeeping issues (R3).\n\n1.3 Emergency access disruption  A site that grows without controlled logistics can lose emergency access, clear egress, and predictable circulation, making response harder during an incident or shutdown (R6).\n\n2. Work Planning Steps (Pre-Task & Pre-Construction)\n\n2.1 Circulation planning  Before active operations begin, the logistics plan should identify worker entry points, delivery routes, waste removal paths, equipment travel lanes, laydown zones, and protected pedestrian movement (R1).\n\n2.2 Sequencing review  Planning should confirm when routes or staging areas change by phase so the site does not continue using outdated paths after new trades, barriers, or structures reduce available space.\n\n2.3 Daily adjustment  As congestion, weather, manpower, or site footprint change, logistics controls should be updated and re-communicated before the shift relies on a route or area that no longer works safely (R2).\n\n3. Structural Stability Requirements\n\n3.1 Surface suitability  Areas used for trailers, gang boxes, laydown, dumpsters, loading zones, ramps, and haul paths should be stable and suitable for the anticipated load, turning movement, and repeated traffic.\n\n3.2 Edge and support review  Temporary slopes, excavation edges, elevated slabs, soft ground, and weather-affected routes should be checked so logistics decisions do not direct traffic into unstable or deteriorated conditions.\n\n4. Connecting & Decking Requirements\n\n4.1 Temporary route setup  Where the logistics plan depends on temporary stairs, ramps, covers, crossings, sidewalk protection, or deck-level walk paths, those items should be installed and maintained before the route is opened for use.\n\n4.2 Continuity of controls  Fencing, barriers, deck openings, gate points, and route markers should remain in place and be updated together so movement stays controlled as the jobsite changes (R1).\n\n5. Training Requirements\n\n5.1 General training  Workers using the site should be instructed on designated entry points, travel paths, restricted areas, delivery zones, PPE expectations, and emergency routes tied to the active logistics plan (R2).\n\n5.2 Task-specific training  Additional instruction may be required for spotters, traffic-control personnel, delivery coordinators, equipment operators, or workers assigned to manage staging and route changes.\n\n5.2.1 Equipment-related training  Only trained or experienced personnel should operate mechanized equipment, direct vehicle movement, or control logistics activities involving powered equipment (R9).\n\n5.2.2 Update training  When routes, gates, laydown areas, or active work zones move, affected crews should be re-briefed so they are not relying on outdated circulation patterns (R7).\n\n6. Certification Requirements\n\n6.1 General applicability  Site logistics planning does not by itself create a standalone certification requirement.\n\n6.2 When certifications apply  Documented qualifications may still be required where logistics activities involve traffic control, equipment operation, rigging, crane support, or another regulated assignment.\n\n7. Required Equipment\n\n7.1 Control equipment  Typical logistics tools include route signs, cones, barricades, fencing, radios, staging markers, lighting, gate hardware, and current layout or traffic-control drawings.\n\n7.2 Support equipment  Depending on the site, logistics planning may also require dumpsters, racks, pallets, temporary walk materials, flagging supplies, and hand tools needed to maintain order and access (R5).\n\n8. Required Permits (If Applicable)\n\n8.1 Route and access permits  Certain logistics activities may depend on permits or approvals for temporary road use, sidewalk closures, crane paths, excavation support, temporary power, or public-space impacts.\n\n8.2 Activation timing  A route or staging zone should not be opened simply because it is needed if the related permit, owner approval, or traffic-control requirement has not been completed.\n\n9. Trades Most Affected by Site Logistics Planning Requirements\n\n9.1 Primary affected parties  These requirements most directly affect supervision, laborers, delivery teams, operators, traffic-control personnel, and every trade relying on predictable access, laydown, and waste removal.\n\n9.2 Shared responsibility  Because site logistics touches every movement on the project, weak planning in one area can delay, crowd, or expose multiple trades across the job.\n\n10. Additional Related Information\n\n10.1 Living plan  Site logistics planning should be treated as a living operational control rather than a one-time startup map because the safe route today may not be the safe route next week (R1).\n\n10.2 Housekeeping connection  Good logistics and good housekeeping support one another because controlled storage, waste handling, and travel paths reduce disorder before it spreads through the work area (R3).\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR1. Employers shall initiate and maintain programs necessary to comply with Part 1926, including frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR2. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. 29 CFR 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR3. Debris, scrap material, and other waste shall be cleared from work areas, passageways, and stairs, and waste shall be removed at frequent and regular intervals. 29 CFR 1926.25(a)-(c).\n\nR5. The employer is responsible for requiring appropriate personal protective equipment where employees are exposed to hazardous conditions. 29 CFR 1926.28(a).\n\nR6. Exits shall be arranged and maintained to provide free and unobstructed egress, and access to exits shall be marked where not immediately visible. 29 CFR 1926.34(a)-(c).\n\nR7. Employees must be trained in a language and vocabulary they can understand, and employers must provide competent person oversight and frequent inspections. OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, General section.\n\nR9. The employer shall permit only those employees qualified by training or experience to operate equipment and machinery. 29 CFR 1926.20(b)(4).\n\nR10. Motor vehicles and mechanized equipment used in off-highway jobsite areas must be operated under jobsite safety controls and maintained with required safety features. 29 CFR 1926.601; OSHA 2202 Construction Industry Digest, Motor Vehicles and Mechanized Equipment.",
